issue.title: SubscriptionController doesn't check if requested repo actually exists
issue.body:
When a request is made to create a new subscription, there's no check (request to Github's API) that actually confirms that the repository exists. The behavior right now is sorta unknown. There might be an IOException trying to parse the response from the cURL request for issues. It more probably just never finds new issues because the repo doesn't exist. 

Desired behavior: we should return a 404 when the subscription request's Github Repo isn't found. Implementation details here are up to you. The front end can elegantly handle the 404 (which we can worry about in a separate issue).

issue.title: Exception Handling via ControllerAdvice
issue.body: We need more graceful and clear exceptions throughout the app's primary workflows. Once those are created and thrown, we should make sure our `GlobalResponseEntityExceptionHandler` has methods to handle those exceptions and return appropriate ResponseEntities

issue.title: Make HTTP Requests to Github's API via RestTemplate
issue.body:
So during the hackathon, using RestTemplate resulted in some weird cert error when making a request to Github's public API. I spent like 4 hours trying to figure out why, and ended up using ProcessBuilder to execute a cURL request instead of using RestTemplate or the like. 

`- GithubRepoService.postForGithubRepoIssues` should use a RestTemplate or something similar to execute an http request to the desired endpoint(s). This RestTemplate should probably be written in the `config` package.
